segments.text: move him around, see him move, we let him run in a circle around us.
And I slapped him on the butt just as he came around one time.
He kicked me on the leg.
I was incapacitated for three months with that one call.
That really ensured my not calling him anymore.
But it is one of those things that happens to you.
Now, did you, within small animal, you're still doing a general practice.
Is there any kind of, you didn't specialize in any facet or anything like that?
Small animals, yes.
I tried to take extra courses and continue the education in ophthalmology and surgery.
And dermatology, particularly dermatology.
I was a member of all those associations at one time to the National Association.
Did you begin any kind of referral practice along the way somewhere?
Yes, we had referrals from surrounding towns, particularly for surgery.
Oh, okay.
So they're coming to you for the surgery and dermatology?
Yes.
How about you now?
Are you referring any of your patients to a specialist?
Oh, yes.
We refer lots to Dallas.
They set up a referral clinic over there that had a very good surgeon, a board man, a board radiologist, and a board dermatologist.
Who is it?
Reedy was a dermatologist.
Reedy?
Okay.
He'll be in this afternoon.
Oh, I'll see him tomorrow, rather.
That's right.
I'll see Reggie tomorrow.
What's his name?
Gosh, he's in here.
He was a surgeon.
He's retired now.
And the radiologist is still there.
She's taking a partner.
She's a ladybird.
And they were very running in a high quality
type thing.
They never tried to give shots and do things like that.
Of course, I was minoring in dermatology, but Reedy was a board man and taught some with the medical school over there.
Because that's the conversion of the profession.
We were very slow at it and very jealous.
They have not accepted it until recent years.
In my time, it was not done hardly at all.
Do you see that as sort of the coming trend in veterinary practice?
Oh, yeah.
Specialization and referral practices?
Quite a lot, yeah.
A general practitioner who basically does the client ministry and then refers the more critical problems?
Yeah, Herman Dietrich was a surgeon.
Herman Dietrich, in fact, I think I may have met him at the...
He might have sat at the table with me.
He lives in Dallas and Colorado.
D-I-E-T-R-I-C-H. One thing we haven't touched on well.
Go ahead.
You go ahead.
You tell me, because that's better.
I don't want to take you too much longer.
Veterans should enter into their local politics and do public work, in my opinion, much more.
There is some classical examples that Dr. Parker from San Antonio, you want to be sure and talk to him.
He was the first veterinarian that was mayor of a large city and was on their board for many years.
He was on the board of the AHA with me at the same time and in the AHA hospital.
Dr. Abels locally has been head of his school board and very active in
his local politics.
Dr. Farrell, J.M.
Farrell, his two brothers, has been very active in his school board, president of it in Arlington.
Very active in local things.
There's others, I can't bring them up right now.
Okay, but that's a good point.
That needs to be the other side.
Yeah.
Earl Waddell was active in Houston.
There's several more down there that I don't...
I'll kind of watch for that as I run along.
What do you think are the major, let's say problems or crises or whatever, I'm not sure that's the right word, far better than the practice?
in this decade, last few decades.
When are you really confronting that?
That seems to be a challenge to the profession.
Well, I missed the county agent deal.
I came in at the tail end of that, and I really don't know enough.
You need to get an older man.
I can get that.
We've got a lot of them now.
We had lots of good fights on that.
Yeah, I know.
I've got that.
Rabies vaccines and stuff.
Well, for one thing, when I was a long year, I had rabies clinics out in the surrounding towns
And that area had a lot of rabies.
I had three in my hospital at one time, rabid animals.
That ain't fun.
That makes you nervous.
No, I've heard a lot of people talk about that.
But the next one I would say is with the druggist selling prescription pharmaceuticals and treating animals, pharmacists treating animals, you know, a farmer comes in, well, you've got a milk fever.
He'd hand him a bottle of dextrose and calcium and not knowing where to put it or anything else, diagnosis.
The next one is our own problem was policing our own ranks for our veterinarians that did not
follow up on their education, and I don't like the word, but just about quacking.
That happened here in Fort Worth.
I went out with the examining board a time or two.
The examining board straightened out a lot of that, pursued those people that weren't up to quality or that were lowering the standards
and violating laws, really, out of the state of Texas.
Right now, one of the big problems are people coming into cities and towns with a mobile clinic, setting up rabies and distempering, anything for half a day to a day's time.
where there are practitioners available to take care of the veterinary practice.
I'm glad you mentioned that.
They're just making a soar and getting the fast trades and the profit business, really.
Is that because of the more intense competition in the business?
Yes.
And that's just one facet of that competition.
I'm glad you mentioned that.

started and it's all over but it's a real fight in the United States now these mobile clinics that uh I'm not talking about the mobile clinic that's in the end down and everything in the phone book yeah this is something else guy comes puts out sheets and has boys delivered to the houses and I'll be at the shopping center uh all day all Sunday
I can see where that would really turn them out, too.
Oh, hell yes.
And a lot of people are, you know, cutting prices.
And that gets back to the advertising problem.
And lower prices are advertised.
Because still, the profession does not condone advertising.
They don't contribute to the community.
They don't pay any taxes on the community.
They don't contribute anything to the community.
It's purely selfish.
How in the world is it going to be combated?
The State Association, I recommend it to the ones here
They set up one right across the street from him and put up a big sign and meet his prices.
That's discouraging, but it's been handled a different way.
You can check in Houston on it.
Dallas has had some of it.
I'll watch for that.
That's a good way to mention it.
What about women in the profession?
Do you have any comments on that?
Women?
When I graduated, there wasn't a woman in the class.
And I've hired as many as four in my time, most of them in my hospitals and branch hospitals.
And they have been very successful.
Yeah, that's the kind of way I've got nothing but praise.
Of course, now they constitute more than half.
Right.
And the graduates coming out of A&M now are most of them.
You should see our local, I wish I'd brought it, got it about yesterday, people are available for practice and people are available for substitutions.
I should get that back to you.
Because that is one of the big problems.
That's a good sign of the times.
OK.
In all due respect, I have kind of muddied the water as far as...
They're part-timers.
They're part-timers.
They're real valuable.
I used to employ military part-timers.
And I went from then to graduate students that had to do work, you know, out with the practitioners.
Missouri started early in...
Nearly all the schools have that they have to go out and work with practitioners anywhere from a month to six months.
And that's very good because they learn economics.
They learn location, locating practices, how important that is, where you make your building.
And they learn relationship with people.
They don't get any of that in schools.
And it's very vital.
You know, you can make it break.
I hired a veterinarian down here, a valedictorian in Colorado, and he'd gone broke in Longview, Tyler, Texas.
Don't print it, but he was held up in a clinic I'd bought.
And he made a living, that's all, for the clinic and himself.
And he decided, Dr. Sears said,
He's a very intelligent guy and has a very intelligent wife.
She was head of her sorority at the University of Texas.
And he said, I'm not happy here.
I want to do some transplant work.
And I've already done a little bit moving muscles here to take care of breaks and stuff.
I said, could I do some college work at TCU and apply to med school?
I said, well, certainly.
And in about a year and a half, he was admitted to Dallas at the university over there.
And when he graduated, he took four of the six honors that they had.
And he's now teaching in San Antonio Medical School.
And he's written the authoritative book of the Bible, they say.
And I had a neighbor that was in it, an orthopedic for children.
Showed me off the beach.
That was his thing.
But I just tell you that everybody is not suited for a practice.
It's better that they learn that and getting out and trying it in practice before they enter into it.
Or learn it early.
That's something you don't learn in school either.
No, not a bit.
And I've kind of picked that up in a lot of conversations I've had with people.
And that is, in practice, you're treating the client as much as you're treating the animal.
Oh, you bet.
You bet.
The psychology of it.
And that's hard to teach your young vets, too.
They're terribly skilled, but they want to listen to the people and get what they...
Sometimes they'll come in and talk one way, but they really want something else.
Bring in an old dog and say, oh, yes, do everything you can.
Then they ask you about the price, and you know underneath they want to put him to sleep, but they won't say it.
You just can't quite come to it.
When I was first here,
I thought I was the euthanasia veterinarian because they'd take it to the regular veterinarian, but they didn't have a nurse enough to tell him to put him to sleep.
There's one old Puerto Rican veterinarian here who wouldn't put the dog to sleep if he had cancer of the throat.
He just wouldn't put him to sleep.
I was taught to save him, not put him to sleep.
I agree with him, but anyway, eventually that caught up.
They have a tendency to take it to another veterinarian when they want to do that.
Yeah, that's interesting.
But I think they're accustomed to the client relationship.
But I want to not leave you an impression I'm critical of women.
No, I don't see that.
But I do see that the nature of the competition, the nature of the business is changing because women are in it.
And they've helped us because they're more gentle with dogs.
And a lot of women would rather bring them to a woman than to a man.
And they are just as good in surgery.
I had one here that did three months work with me and then came to me as a veterinarian.
And I've never had a sharper person that I could talk over a case.
We would enjoy working together all night.
But one didn't think the other would.
And a fellow bought me out.
And he didn't jive with her.
And he'd been my partner, too.
He was in his practice at the same time she was there.
And I recommended it to his brother, who had another partnership practice I'd had.
And she's with him and her right-hand man.
And she carried a lot of practice over there with her.
When she left mine, I never could understand why this didn't work out.
Well, they had another fellow they wanted to bring in, and primarily couldn't afford two of them.
The other fellow was not her caliber at all.
I interviewed Anelda Bates in San Antonio.
I don't know if you remember her.
She's apparently one of the early practitioners in Texas.
came out of Purdue, I believe.
I had an Illinois one, and I hired her as a substitute lots of times.
She was very good.
Worked out of Dallas.
I guess we better go ahead and close then, but if you were going to write a book on veterinary medicine, what do you think would be the main thing you would want to express or explain in that book?
I would think that of our
Dentistry and MDs, DOs, we have kept pace with them.
We have been leaders in some.
And we're not to be, take a second seat to them in the practice of medicine in any respect.
I really think that
then your medicine has done proud for itself with not too much help.
And this is the main thing that the public needs to know, you think?
I think so.
I'm very active in Morris Animal Foundation now.
And it is a group that is headquartered in Denver.
started by Dr. Morris, who invented KD, RD, and all these special diets that veterinarians use.
And it is dedicated to research in animal diseases that are not covered by the US government.
And that means dog, cat, horse, and zoo.
I feel that it's a very beneficial thing, and they do more research through the colleges, through the veterinary colleges.
They fund research.
They fund research than anyone else in the United States.
Cornell is second, and it drops off terribly up in there.
The Texas and AVMA and AHA have copied it
But they don't have anything like the money spent.
Yeah.
I gather that's one of the, I read the Pew report, and I think that's one of them.
Yeah.
Give them a plug, because they deserve it.
Yeah.
Dr. Morris gave a certain percent of his profits to this organization.
One of my clients here was president, president of the board of directors.
and very active in setting up a fund, which they do.
They pay for the research off the income from this fund.
It's a stable fund, and the fund pays enough interest money that they do not have to enter into the principal.
And the state board, as a member of the state veterinary board,
at one time as an honor for being that.
And I enjoyed that relationship with my clients.
The state TVMA doesn't have money or resources to fund research projects.
Very much.
They have a little bit.
I know the foundation is trying to develop in that area.
Well, Fort Worth had its own foundation.
Is that right?
We formed it very soon after the Morris Animal Foundation
And we have $60,000 that this man gave us in the bank right now to devote to research and to... We've spent a lot... For a local organization, that's very good.
Well, we're the only one, practically in the United States, that we also set up our own loan fund.
If you'll check at the college down there, we have had and still maintain a loan fund
for veterinary students.

That was part of our... Is there a sense, you think, in the profession now that too many veterinarians are coming out into the practice through... Well, I've been on a long-range planning committee twice several years back, and now I'm on it now.
And that's a continual problem.
I would...
I think so.
You can hire veterinarians pretty cheap now compared to...
four or five years ago, and yet the good ones are bringing good salary.
I have two daughters in dietetics, and they don't fall into a veterinarian's price range, a graduating one, and a graduating dietitian, and it's about the same amount of school work.
Theirs has come up fast, too.
I had one other thing I wanted to mention to you.
I alluded to it back there with Glenn Savage and King.
I had to fire King's organization because Dr.
Cloud, my treasurer, thought we were getting the shaft as far as expenses.
He came in and doubled the dues the first month he was in.
He got it passed through.
And then he wanted to double them again in two years' time that every member paid.
And we found out, well, you forced an audit, Dr.
Cloud and I.
on to him, and I have letters and all kinds of things through the years brought along.
And he fought it all the way.
What he would do is put out printing, charge us one price, and pay them about half.
And he'd do it different with his charges, his work that he did, slides work, and stuff like that, much up from what
Well, anyway, at the same time, he had us as his executive secretary.
He's the executive secretary of the Texas Cattle Racers Association and Texas Truckers Association and several more.
Both of those sued him after we fired him and won their court trials.
This didn't get much publicity.
And I got some criticism from it.
Sounded like you did the right thing without any reservation.
Yeah.
And I have lots of letters and proof and so forth.
Yeah, I'm sure that was a tough time for you to do.
He wrote me a letter that in effect said that I was going to apologize to him, accept his audit, and rehire him, or he's going to send it to every member of the state association
And he called me a SOB.
And he gave me a time from Thursday till Sunday to give him a signed copy of a different letter that he wanted me to send.
And I got the letter and came in, got the old business, came home for lunch.
Well, I said, what in the world happened to you?
He said, you look funny.
I said, well, read this letter.
And she said, does he mean that?
Said he's going to send it to every member.
I've got a copy here.
To the association.
If I didn't notify him by Saturday noon.
And she says, what are you going to do?
And I said, I'm going to Abilene.
And she said, what the hell are you going to Abilene for?
I said, that won't solve this problem.
I said, well, he can't call me.
And I said, I'm going to call his bluff.
I said, if he sends that out, I'm going to sue him.
And he knows all of a sudden.
And he said, that's Mark.
Well, I did.
And he didn't, nothing came of it.
But he accepted it with ill grace and continually wrote my board and wrote the board of directors and the officers without sending me copies and stuff.
But we got rid of him.
And about five years, he went crazy and died.
early.
He had a mental problem.
He was trying to go too far.
That's hard.
That's hard on you, too.
I won't do anything without...
Some of us remember it, but the people following me and Julef down at... Yeah, I've talked to him.
He was the one that hired him.
And he was... Well, Julef realizes what it got into me.
I think we're through.
We've got company coming.
